To determine whether an integer `n` is a power of three without using loops or recursion in Java, you can take advantage of the fact that any power of three can be expressed as `3^k` for some integer `k`. Using this observation, you can check if `n` can be represented as `3^(k)` by repeatedly dividing `n` by `3` while keeping track of the number of times `n` is divided (i.e., the exponent `k`). If `n` is eventually reduced to 1 after such division, then `k` represents the power of three that equals `n`.

Here's a Java implementation that checks if `n` is a power of three based on this approach:

```java
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n <= 0 || (n & (n - 1)) != 0) { // handle non-positive/non-power-of-two inputs
        return false;
    }

    int k = 0; // initialize power-of-three exponent counter
    while (n > 1) { // iterate until n becomes 1
        if (n % 3 != 0) { // if n is not divisible by 3, cannot be a power of three
            return false;
        }
        k++; // increment power-of-three exponent
        n /= 3; // divide n by 3 to move towards 1
    }

    return k > 0; // nonzero power-of-three exponent implies n is a power of three
}
```

This implementation first checks for invalid inputs by ensuring that `n` is positive and not a power of two minus one (since any such number has no corresponding power of three). Then, it initializes a counter `k` to keep track of the power-of-three exponent.

The main loop iterates while `n > 1`, repeatedly dividing `n` by `3` to move closer to a possible power-of-three representation. If at any point `n` is not divisible by `3`, then there is no way to express `n` as a power of three with a positive integer exponent, and the method returns `false`. Otherwise, `k` increments each time `n` is divided by `3`, accumulating the potential power-of-three exponent.

Finally, returning `k > 0` ensures that a nonzero power-of-three exponent implies `n` can be expressed as a power of three by setting `k` to the corresponding value.

